WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:05.340
Hi, this is Brian, and welcome to the Designing Open Democracy Podcast.

2
00:00:05.340 --> 00:00:11.660
We are an Australian-based forum, keeping track of democracy, innovation in Australia and around the world.

3
00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:23.080
For this episode recorded on the 3rd of March 2020, I visited a prominent Australian economist named Nicholas Gruen, CEO of Lateral Economics.

4
00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:35.900
As frequent commentator on economic reforms as well as innovation, he will be joining us for this episode to explore the concept of citizen juries and how it could be implemented in Australia and other countries.

5
00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:42.420
So let's start with a short introduction of Nicholas Gruen, as well as a summary of the whole talk we will cover.

6
00:00:42.420 --> 00:00:47.180
So Nicholas, can you give me a quick rundown of who you are and what you do?

7
00:00:47.180 --> 00:00:49.120
Yeah, so my name is Nicholas Gruen.

8
00:00:49.120 --> 00:00:52.380
I run an economic consultancy called Lateral Economics.

9
00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:57.960
I've had a long history in policymaking and have been an advisor to politicians.

10
00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:01.500
So I've seen politics up close for about 30 years.

11
00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:18.460
And I'm pretty concerned, have been concerned for at least 20 years with how shallow and what I call fast foodified and divisive and polarizing politics is at the moment, democratic politics is at the moment.

12
00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:28.400
And I think there is a big and simple thing that we can do to make fairly substantial change and improvement.

13
00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:39.080
And definitely in the talk, we will talk a bit more about the origin of the concept of Isagora and how ancient Athens used to do their democracy.

14
00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:45.540
And from there, we're going to be going into this concept, which are talk about of a citizen juries.

15
00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:47.080
So can you talk more about that?

16
00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:47.460
Sure.

17
00:01:47.460 --> 00:01:56.140
So the way in which we have representatives of the public in politics is we, they're the winners of elections.

18
00:01:56.160 --> 00:02:02.600
And we actually have another mechanism for having representatives of the public.

19
00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:05.420
And we do that in our legal system with juries.

20
00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:09.100
And the way we have representatives of the public is very different.

21
00:02:09.100 --> 00:02:21.280
We don't really think of any individual as a representative of the public, but we think of the jury, particularly when it can come to consensus, as a consensus which represents the community.

22
00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:32.420
And for a whole host of reasons that I hope we'll explore, this represents a very different way to represent democratic views.

23
00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:34.620
It's more considered.

24
00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:48.980
The psychology of it's different, because people aren't trying to beat each other, they're trying to get to, they're trying to understand each other, and then to compromise to get to some kind of solution.

25
00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:55.720
For that and a range of other reasons that we can discuss, I think we need to inject that into our democracy.

26
00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:59.120
So we don't talk about getting rid of anything we have.

27
00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:19.100
I would like to say, so if you want to know what this means in terms of a concrete plan, I would like in 10 years, 20 years time for there to be a House of Parliament, whether it replaces the Senate or is in addition to the Senate, which represents the Australian people in the way the jury represents the Australian people.

28
00:03:19.100 --> 00:03:25.820
That is, its members are chosen randomly from the community to be reflective of the community.

29
00:03:26.680 --> 00:03:39.180
And I would like that body to be treated just like a House of Parliament so that legislation and motions and so on need to go through it as well as the House of Parliament we have now.

30
00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:45.780
Now, that won't be government funded and built into our Constitution any time soon.

31
00:03:45.780 --> 00:04:00.380
The exciting thing is that if we can crowd source the funding for that, we can set up the governance quite separately from Parliament, quite separately from any existing government, and we can have that sitting there.

32
00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:25.380
And what it would do is while the Democrats, while the Houses of Parliament tell us what the parties want and what their backers want, while opinion polls tell us what the opinion of the people is on numerous things, this Citizens' Assembly, a Standing Citizens' Assembly, would show us what the considered opinion of the Australian people is.

33
00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:35.480
And over time, I think, as people saw how well that worked, they would start saying, we want that as part of our political system, and it would be brought into the political system.

34
00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:38.580
So that's the trajectory that I would like to see.

35
00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:51.000
And what's exciting about it is that it's quite a radical, or it's a pretty strong idea for reform, but it isn't something that we have to go and get permission from anyone to start.

36
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.640
We can raise the money ourselves and start doing it now.

37
00:04:54.640 --> 00:05:01.440
So it sounds like you explained what the Citizen Juries is, and also in some ways how you could implement it.

38
00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:06.660
Before we go into potentially the main talk, how will people join you?

39
00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:09.540
Well, they can, at the moment, they should just email me.

40
00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:11.480
I'll give you my email on this podcast.

41
00:05:11.580 --> 00:05:25.800
It's ngruen, six letters, n for Nicholas, g-r-u-e-n, g-r for Richard, u-e-n at gmail.com, and I'll put your name on a mailing list, and you'll just get updates.

42
00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:29.220
But I'm hoping to have some news about this.

43
00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:44.300
I'm constantly trying to bring this vision about in different ways, with different demonstration projects in different parts of the world, actually, and happy to put you on a mailing list and keep you up to date.

44
00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:45.320
Thank you very much.

45
00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:53.660
And of course, if people are interested in the general workings of improvement designing open democracy, they could always join us, designingopendemocracy.com.

46
00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:04.940
So this is the end of the overall summary of this talk, which will help provide the context to what Nicholas Gruen will be elaborating over the following hour-long talk.

47
00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:11.940
Our first topic was about Isagoria and how it relates to the idea of citizen juries.

48
00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:20.640
So, a while ago, I was having a chat with Nicholas Gruen about some of his efforts, and we will talk a bit about ancient Athens.

49
00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:28.680
And the thing he wanted me to know more about was the concept of Isagora, but I didn't really quite understand Isagora.

50
00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:30.840
So this is why we have him here today.

51
00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:38.680
And of course, we will talk a little bit more about what he really wants to push forward, which is this idea of citizen juries.

52
00:06:38.680 --> 00:06:43.680
Would you like to take it from here and explain what's this idea of Isagora from ancient Athens?

53
00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:49.920
So, the ancient Athenians had a number of, they thought about their politics.

54
00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:57.880
Ancient Athens is the first democracy of any scale recorded in history.

55
00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:01.700
And they had two concepts.

56
00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:14.100
They probably had plenty of others, but one of them, they used the ancient Greek word parhessia, and that is often translated as freedom of speech.

57
00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:18.840
In fact, it means the duty to speak truth to power.

58
00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:27.200
But that's just for a bit of relief against this other concept.

59
00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:36.000
At least we have a concept in our democracy of freedom of speech, which is a little similar to that ancient Athenian concept.

60
00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:44.200
The other concept in ancient Athenian democracy, which was known by the word issegoria.

61
00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:47.420
I don't know whether that's a great way to pronounce it.

62
00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:55.400
My wife is Greek, but then she's modern Greek, and I don't know whether she's a good guide either, but I pronounce it issegoria.

63
00:07:56.180 --> 00:08:17.600
And what it means is something which we don't really think about in our politics, but it struck me that it's a fantastically good description of something which is absent from our politics, and our lack of a word for it, our lack of a concept of it means that we don't think about it very much.

64
00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:22.180
And the concept of issegoria means equality of speech.

65
00:08:23.140 --> 00:08:28.640
So why don't we have equality of speech in our democracy?

66
00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:37.059
Because, for instance, all those people who aren't particularly well educated, they're not really represented that well.

67
00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:53.260
Their way of thinking and speaking isn't represented in parliament because of something like 95% of members of parliament are highly educated, if you take as highly educated someone who has a university degree or more.

68
00:08:53.260 --> 00:09:18.020
That means that the whole way our political discourse is conducted is conducted in a way that alienates a large, you know, something like 40, 50% of our population, or at least leaves them with a feeling that things are being discussed in a way that is different to the way they think about those things.

69
00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:28.880
And in fact, it's got worse than that because in the last 10, 15 years, there has been a huge ramping up of political correctness.

70
00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:35.320
And therefore, certain ways of speaking are simply proscribed.

71
00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:39.360
They're simply prohibited if you use those forms of speech.

72
00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:47.820
People come after you and call you a racist and a sexist and a transphobic and Islamophobic and all the rest of it.

73
00:09:47.820 --> 00:10:01.180
And so the issues that people care a lot about, a lot of people care about immigration or used to, I think they're a bit less concerned about it now.

74
00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:06.020
And I don't say this is someone who is all that sympathetic to that concern.

75
00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:08.980
I am sympathetic to it if people care about it.

76
00:10:08.980 --> 00:10:16.880
This is supposed to be a democracy and they're supposed to be able to express their view and that is supposed to be discussed in our democracy.

77
00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:22.700
But if you say, and again, I repeat, I don't agree with this.

78
00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:29.140
But if you say, I don't think we should have, I think we should have lower immigration.

79
00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:41.700
If you say pretty much anything about immigration, God forbid, you say we should have certain kinds of immigrants and not other kinds of immigrants, then that is regarded as outrageous, beyond the pale and all the rest of it.

80
00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:44.160
Well, okay.

81
00:10:44.160 --> 00:10:58.380
But that's going to leave a lot of people feeling that they're not actually part of a functioning democracy there in some other game, in which the way they think is actually being actively suppressed and attacked.

82
00:10:59.560 --> 00:11:04.520
So, you feel that our current system of proportional representation doesn't capture the...

83
00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:06.780
Well, we don't have proportional representation.

84
00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:20.060
We have, in the House of Representatives, we have single member electorates, and we elect the party or the member who has the highest two-party preferred vote.

85
00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:23.000
And we have some proportional representation in the Senate.

86
00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:31.120
I think we should remind the audience, if they're not from Australia, that what we're referring to is the Australian political system at the moment.

87
00:11:31.120 --> 00:11:40.300
Yeah, but what I'm talking about is the idea that, and here's a shocking thought, you can have a democracy without elections.

88
00:11:40.300 --> 00:11:44.600
Now, I'm not actually proposing a democracy without elections, but that's a shocking thought.

89
00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:50.560
There's one obvious way you can have a democracy without elections, and some people are quite fond of it, but I'm not.

90
00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:55.140
And then there's this other way of having a democracy without elections.

91
00:11:55.740 --> 00:12:01.840
The way many people can relate to is the idea of direct democracy, which is that everybody gets a vote about everything.

92
00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:07.620
And that's sort of what they had in ancient Athens, or it was a bit more structured than that.

93
00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:13.120
Yes, we were talking about ancient Athens, so I would definitely like to learn a bit more about it.

94
00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:17.120
And I remember you say that there's Isagora, and it is part of ancient Athens.

95
00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:21.820
So is it like, what's the direct link between Isagora and ancient Athens?

96
00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:24.440
Well, I said that.

97
00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:32.460
Like freedom of speech is important in our democracy, equality of speech was a fundamental part of ancient Athens.

98
00:12:32.460 --> 00:12:38.600
And the two institutions that delivered equality of speech was Direct Democracy, which I don't greatly support.

99
00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:42.960
But that was a monthly meeting of a thing called the Ecclesia.

100
00:12:42.960 --> 00:13:01.700
And the Ecclesia is a council, is all citizens now, as people always remind you, citizens didn't include slaves, it didn't include women, and it didn't include people who might be permanent residents in Athens, but were foreigners.

101
00:13:01.700 --> 00:13:05.080
That's obviously not something I'm saying is a good idea.

102
00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:09.940
Anyway, that was how, that was their form of Direct Democracy.

103
00:13:09.940 --> 00:13:11.580
They would meet once a month.

104
00:13:11.580 --> 00:13:23.820
However, all the nitty gritty matters, including what the Ecclesia, the Assembly, what they discussed was set up for them.

105
00:13:23.820 --> 00:13:27.700
Their agenda was set up for, but by I think all the Boulay.

106
00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:35.740
And the Boulay was 500 people, citizens chosen at random and rotated every year.

107
00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:42.660
Every year, there'd be 500 different people chosen at random from the community in the way that we choose juries.

108
00:13:42.660 --> 00:13:52.380
And that was the body that ran the city, maintained the buildings, collected rubbish, if there was any government collecting of rubbish, I don't know.

109
00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:57.640
And was very important in setting up the agenda for the assembly.

110
00:13:57.640 --> 00:14:06.540
And both of those institutions are very much into isegory or equality of speech.

111
00:14:06.540 --> 00:14:12.000
In other words, you don't have to win an election to be a part of any of this.

112
00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.320
If you want to win an election, you have to have to be articulate.

113
00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:18.900
You likely have to be well-educated.

114
00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:23.300
You have to have some money or have some friends with money.

115
00:14:25.760 --> 00:14:33.580
And that produces a perversion of democracy in a range of ways that we're becoming more and more familiar.

116
00:14:34.020 --> 00:14:36.220
We kind of experience more and more.

117
00:14:36.220 --> 00:14:43.940
So these two institutions that ran Athenian democracy, didn't have elections and so were much more...

118
00:14:43.940 --> 00:14:46.900
there was much more equality of speech in that system.

119
00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:48.740
I see.

120
00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:53.480
So that is definitely an interesting look into ancient Athens.

121
00:14:53.480 --> 00:14:57.100
And it's something that I imagine a lot of people are not super familiar.

122
00:14:57.100 --> 00:15:01.640
But what most people would already be familiar is our current system.

123
00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:08.660
And it seems like there's a problem with democracy that it doesn't quite seem to work for them.

124
00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:18.880
And I remember a while ago, you mentioned something about how the current system is based on the opinion of the people, not the considered opinion of the people.

125
00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:25.520
And this sounds like it relates to what you're seeing as going wrong with our current society.

126
00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:26.780
That's right.

127
00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:39.780
So the other way to represent the people, one way is having elections and everybody can say, oh, well, they represent me because I got a vote as to who that person should be.

128
00:15:39.780 --> 00:15:44.920
I might have lost the vote, but at least I know in my area, the majority of people voted for that person.

129
00:15:44.920 --> 00:15:51.860
And that guarantees me there is some sense, there is some democratic legitimacy to that.

130
00:15:51.860 --> 00:15:57.240
There's now the problem is we purchase that legitimacy at the expense of equality of speech.

131
00:15:57.240 --> 00:16:02.440
There is a certain kind of person who overwhelmingly wins that contest.

132
00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:07.220
The alternative we have in our courts of law.

133
00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:23.980
So if you want to find out if somebody is guilty of something, we have a democratic institution there, so that at the end of a court case, we can say not just that the court found this person guilty, but that the community found them guilty.

134
00:16:23.980 --> 00:16:26.200
And that's what we have with the jury.

135
00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:26.540
So we...

136
00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:28.140
I'm sorry, you want to say something?

137
00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:41.720
No, I'd like to continue your one, but I've found this really interesting in the sense that when you're saying the court system, like it hasn't always run that way, if I remember, back in the medieval time, is it before the Magna Carta?

138
00:16:41.720 --> 00:16:46.120
Well, Magna Carta is 1215, I think, so it's a long time ago.

139
00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:51.820
So medieval is after that, really, but in the sort of dark ages before that, it's a much murkier story.

140
00:16:51.820 --> 00:17:04.920
Yeah, if I remember back then, before our current justice system, it was actually more based on like inquisitorial kind of justice, where the judge does both the investigation and the prosecution.

141
00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:21.579
But if I understand about our new modern justice system, it's more of a separation of the prosecutorial element of the judge, to make the judge a more impartial figure, so that you have a competition between the defense and the prosecution.

142
00:17:21.579 --> 00:17:29.100
Well, that's true, and I've also written about that, but the element that I think is relevant here is the jury.

143
00:17:29.100 --> 00:17:55.440
And the jury, the significance of the jury, from my point of view, is that just as I was saying there is some legitimacy in Parliament, because we voted for Parliament, there is some legitimacy if 12 ordinary people chosen at random all say, or say 10 out of the 12 say, that an accused is guilty on the facts as presented to them.

144
00:17:55.440 --> 00:18:06.460
They've been through the trial, they've looked at the evidence, they've had it all presented to them, they've had as much time as they wanted to, to deliberate and consider their verdict, and they come up with a verdict.

145
00:18:06.460 --> 00:18:15.340
So what that does is that it produces another way to determine what the people's view is.

146
00:18:15.340 --> 00:18:28.320
But it does it not by way of a competition, which has a bunch of problems with it, but by simply sampling from the community, a random sample of the community.

147
00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:41.400
And then what we get out of that is we get the considered opinion of the community, because we don't have the time, all of us, to learn all about a particular court case.

148
00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:43.280
And there are lots of court cases going on.

149
00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:47.460
So if we want to learn about one court case, there are hundreds of court cases to be settled.

150
00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:51.100
So the way we deal with that is through juries.

151
00:18:51.100 --> 00:18:55.820
And we could do a lot more of that in our political system.

152
00:18:55.820 --> 00:19:02.860
And if we did that, that would address questions like the lack of a quality of speech.

153
00:19:02.860 --> 00:19:09.960
It would also address questions like the difference between the opinion of the people and the considered opinion of the people.

154
00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:27.100
Because for instance, when Tony Abbott campaigned in Australia to abolish the carbon pricing of the previous government, he knew that if a radio interviewer wanted to talk about it, he'd have to talk about it for a minute or two, and then that would be the end of it.

155
00:19:27.100 --> 00:19:32.520
So he was able to bring to government a policy that really didn't make any sense.

156
00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:40.300
And if a jury had considered that policy, they would have said, well, here's the policy you object to, which is carbon pricing.

157
00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:41.700
We've looked at your...

158
00:19:41.700 --> 00:19:44.120
And now, okay, you've got some objections to carbon pricing.

159
00:19:44.120 --> 00:19:44.840
That's fair enough.

160
00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.740
We've looked at your policy, and it doesn't really make any sense.

161
00:19:48.740 --> 00:19:49.460
It's not...

162
00:19:49.460 --> 00:19:54.700
You're claiming that it will do the same thing at a lower cost, and it won't do anything of the kind.

163
00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:56.940
It simply isn't a policy.

164
00:19:56.940 --> 00:20:00.160
So that's why it's important to...

165
00:20:01.020 --> 00:20:13.560
So by involving juries in politics more, I'm not talking about abandoning elections, but involving juries more, we can solve a number of problems.

166
00:20:13.660 --> 00:20:22.220
And one is the problem of a quality of speech, and the other is the problem that we want the considered opinion of the people involved, not just the opinion of the people.

167
00:20:22.220 --> 00:20:33.380
So in some ways, what you're saying is you want to also implement a way of providing closer scrutiny of the policies that has been put forward to the people.

168
00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:34.480
Sure, sure.

169
00:20:34.480 --> 00:20:44.840
And I want it to be less about a media circus, and more about groups of people trying to figure out what the right answer is, and not really whose side they're on.

170
00:20:44.840 --> 00:20:55.680
So so much of modern politics involves people self-identifying with one side or the other, which is fine, but we want to work these problems out.

171
00:20:55.680 --> 00:21:03.640
And usually both sides have something to say, and various people who aren't in parliament at all have something to say.

172
00:21:03.640 --> 00:21:15.220
If you're making the argument of using the court system as an analogy in some ways, wouldn't you say that you have to defend under prosecution, and obviously you want both of them to make the strongest case?

173
00:21:15.220 --> 00:21:18.620
Yes, sure, that's one way to, that's one analogy.

174
00:21:18.620 --> 00:21:35.940
But yeah, you don't necessarily, there will be times when the two party, the two major parties fighting with each other, won't actually give you the answer you want, because both of them are, you've heard of this expression, certainly in Australia, we have the expression of small target strategy.

175
00:21:35.940 --> 00:21:48.100
Now, a small target strategy is a strategy that a major party, typically a major party has, and the idea is that they can get through an election without any people attacking them.

176
00:21:50.100 --> 00:22:08.440
So, they know each of them go into the election with about 40% of the vote, and they're just trying to make sure that nobody gets too upset about with them, so that they can stay on message during the election campaign and keep saying what they want to say rather than just defending one policy after another.

177
00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:11.060
So they adopt a small target strategy.

178
00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:16.060
And there are lots of areas where we've got a rough idea what to do.

179
00:22:16.320 --> 00:22:21.660
So to give you an example, gun control is an example in the United States.

180
00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:25.240
Mass incarceration is an example in the United States.

181
00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:34.760
Treating drug problems more for harm minimization and as a medical issue rather than as a criminal issue is an issue around the world.

182
00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:51.800
And politicians are just scared to do what the people who are experts in the field think ought to be done because they're afraid that they will be presented as not tough enough on crime and all that sort of stuff.

183
00:22:51.800 --> 00:22:53.820
I see.

184
00:22:53.820 --> 00:23:02.640
Well, going to current affairs, like if you remember, there's America, election going on, there's Bill Sanders, there's Bloomberg and all sorts.

185
00:23:02.640 --> 00:23:07.340
And if I remember, Bloomberg approached to, as a mayor, was stop and frisk.

186
00:23:07.340 --> 00:23:15.980
And it was very much on the idea of providing a very strong kind of like image to the population that just tough on crime.

187
00:23:15.980 --> 00:23:16.640
That's right.

188
00:23:16.640 --> 00:23:20.140
And it sounds like it almost relates to what you were talking about.

189
00:23:20.140 --> 00:23:21.100
I think it does, actually.

190
00:23:21.100 --> 00:23:22.580
I think that's rather a good example.

191
00:23:22.580 --> 00:23:28.140
I think if there were citizens, so what happened with stop and frisk?

192
00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:32.680
And I'm no expert on this, so I may need to be corrected.

193
00:23:32.680 --> 00:23:42.400
But as I understand it, Mayor Bloomberg was able to sell the idea of stop and frisk as him being tough on crime, and people wanted to be tough on crime.

194
00:23:42.400 --> 00:24:00.760
And that morphed into a process of policing that the black community experienced as deeply racist, because in many ways, because the way the police policed was more or less to assume they were guilty until they proved...

195
00:24:00.760 --> 00:24:03.880
Black people were guilty until they proved otherwise.

196
00:24:03.880 --> 00:24:06.860
So there's lots of evidence that if you were...

197
00:24:06.860 --> 00:24:11.900
There's a nice line where someone was found guilty of driving while black.

198
00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:27.160
So the idea was if you were black and driving a decent looking car, you'd be stopped and frisked and people would assume you were a drug dealer and all this kind of stuff.

199
00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:41.920
Now, I think that if the black community came to a citizen jury and said, we feel this is deeply wrong and we want to take you to look at what happens.

200
00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:44.120
And we think you'll understand this.

201
00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:46.900
I think a lot of people would have reacted well to that.

202
00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:48.360
I may be wrong.

203
00:24:48.360 --> 00:24:57.480
Certainly in the South in the 1950s and 60s, white juries used to acquit white people of raping black women.

204
00:24:57.480 --> 00:25:02.300
So, you know, it's possible that I'm not suggesting this mechanism is perfect.

205
00:25:02.300 --> 00:25:10.820
If there's enough vicious racism around, then democracy works as you would expect democracy to work.

206
00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:23.780
I would be very curious in following that line of thought later on when we start comparing your concepts against other competing democracy concepts like flux, my vote, as well as proportion of representation.

207
00:25:23.780 --> 00:25:25.320
Yeah.

208
00:25:25.320 --> 00:25:27.340
Well, look, I'm no expert on these things.

209
00:25:27.340 --> 00:25:29.220
I've had a look at them all.

210
00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:32.500
I kind of wish them well, obviously.

211
00:25:33.140 --> 00:25:34.840
Oh, well, should we provide context?

212
00:25:34.900 --> 00:25:38.500
Yeah, you explain one model and I'll comment on.

213
00:25:38.500 --> 00:25:48.400
If I remembered, the concept of flux and my vote is about providing a representation that is controlled through digital direct democracy.

214
00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:48.700
Yeah.

215
00:25:48.700 --> 00:25:55.180
But in some ways, if I understand the flux, it's based on issue-based direct democracy.

216
00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:56.700
That's how they name it.

217
00:25:56.820 --> 00:25:57.400
I understand.

218
00:25:57.400 --> 00:26:12.660
And the idea is for every issue, you get to choose which issue you want to vote for, and if you don't trust yourself, that's a direct democracy approach, but you don't trust yourself, you could delegate to another person.

219
00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:13.240
That's right.

220
00:26:13.240 --> 00:26:17.400
And there's a bit more complication to it as well, in terms of being able to save up.

221
00:26:17.400 --> 00:26:24.140
But if you're interested in this, you might as well listen to the other talk I have with Ben Bellingle on the flux system.

222
00:26:24.540 --> 00:26:25.180
Yeah.

223
00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:33.680
So my reaction to this is firstly, I wish them well and I think it's an interesting experiment.

224
00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:44.420
They have to, as I understand what they're doing, they have to campaign as a party because they want to get into parliament with flux candidates.

225
00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:56.180
And so in campaigning, they will need to adopt some of the kinds of compromises that candidates do.

226
00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:59.580
So they'll have to explain themselves in under eight seconds.

227
00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:00.980
They will simplify.

228
00:27:00.980 --> 00:27:09.940
They will find ways of expressing themselves that are highly emotive and so on.

229
00:27:09.940 --> 00:27:10.580
Good luck to them.

230
00:27:10.580 --> 00:27:12.300
I'm not saying that's a terrible thing.

231
00:27:12.300 --> 00:27:26.340
I'm simply saying they're drawn into the existing system and the existing system exerts forces on people because politicians are the way they are, not because they're bad people, but because they're trying to win elections.

232
00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:28.500
They're trying to win our vote.

233
00:27:28.500 --> 00:27:35.620
And one of my big points here is that we're every bit as much of the problem of politics as the politicians are.

234
00:27:35.620 --> 00:27:47.660
And a lot of activism, a lot of people saying they're going to fix democracy, are suckers for a view that we're the good guys and the politicians are the bad guys.

235
00:27:47.660 --> 00:27:55.420
We're all part of a system, and the politicians don't act the way they do because they're bad people.

236
00:27:55.420 --> 00:28:00.740
They act the way they do because we reward them for acting in that way.

237
00:28:00.740 --> 00:28:10.400
So the clear word you would probably say is that there's a perverse incentive baked into our current system, which means that when you try to work to it, it's much harder to actually do it.

238
00:28:10.400 --> 00:28:12.580
Yes, but let's be more frank about it.

239
00:28:12.580 --> 00:28:17.520
We vote for, we complain about lack of leadership.

240
00:28:17.520 --> 00:28:21.880
We complain about politicians' scare campaigns.

241
00:28:21.880 --> 00:28:24.700
And why do you think they run scare campaigns?

242
00:28:24.700 --> 00:28:28.860
Because they sort of temperamentally like scare campaigns?

243
00:28:28.860 --> 00:28:32.080
Of course not, because scare campaigns work.

244
00:28:32.080 --> 00:28:39.040
Scare campaigns influence our votes, and everyone knows who is a political operative.

245
00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:44.360
So don't come, so don't tell us how evil the politicians are.

246
00:28:44.360 --> 00:28:47.280
We are the people who make the votes.

247
00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:50.400
This is a complete system.

248
00:28:50.420 --> 00:29:02.380
And so my concern about direct democracy is that it, we're still thinking of ourselves as the good guys.

249
00:29:04.940 --> 00:29:28.920
And all of the ways in which I see the current system as perverse and very bad and inadequate are likely to be similar in direct democracy, maybe a bit better, but it's entirely possible that it works.

250
00:29:29.460 --> 00:29:33.560
So, let's take the example that I just gave you.

251
00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:37.940
Politicians use scare campaigns because they work.

252
00:29:37.940 --> 00:29:53.900
So, if we have a direct vote on a carbon tax or franking credits or any other damn thing, the political system will seek to manipulate people, to scare people, to win their votes.

253
00:29:55.400 --> 00:30:28.680
If we then ask, what would happen if we had a chamber of parliament in which a hundred people were chosen at random from the Australian community, and they got to talk about stuff and call experts, just as the other two houses of parliament can, and commission reports, then I think you have a chance to stand against the circus, the carry-on that we have in our current system.

254
00:30:28.680 --> 00:30:43.460
And the idea that we can reform the current system and build into a direct, but by making the democracy more direct, I think is quite likely not to solve the problem and might make things worse.

255
00:30:43.480 --> 00:30:44.320
I see.

256
00:30:44.320 --> 00:30:44.820
I see.

257
00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:51.940
There's also MyVote, and there's definitely a difference.

258
00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:55.380
But one of the things I could say about MyVote is their approach.

259
00:30:55.380 --> 00:31:18.100
At the moment, from what I understand, is to not be a party, but to provide a system for candidates that want to adopt the MyVote system, to be able to allow their own members in their own party to vote for and decide and help inform the representative on what the members want you to vote as.

260
00:31:18.100 --> 00:31:33.460
And part of the things I think that MyVote does want to address in a similar method about the considered opinion of the people is the idea of creating information package that is accompanied with the voting system.

261
00:31:33.460 --> 00:31:42.980
It sounds like you're not too convinced about that approach because even if it's similar to the idea of trying to tackle the considered opinion of the people problem.

262
00:31:42.980 --> 00:31:43.520
Yeah.

263
00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:52.400
Well, I think that they're trying to think of the problems and they've come to similar conclusions to me about what the problems are.

264
00:31:52.400 --> 00:32:02.780
I think that they're pretty keen on the idea of there being a technological solution and the technological solution is an app is an important part of it.

265
00:32:02.780 --> 00:32:06.920
And I'm the less optimistic that they can do that.

266
00:32:07.380 --> 00:32:12.880
Let me make a few observations that are not necessarily very systematic.

267
00:32:15.280 --> 00:32:19.800
Firstly, intuitively, I don't like the idea of packaging up.

268
00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:31.320
I mean, this is what parties do, but they package up bunches of issues and say, well, here are four or ten alternatives and you can vote for one of those alternatives.

269
00:32:31.320 --> 00:32:40.600
Decisions are made on specific, our political system will make decisions on thousands of very specific things.

270
00:32:40.600 --> 00:32:46.180
And I'm not, I've never been myself comfortable with saying, oh, I'm here on the political spectrum.

271
00:32:46.180 --> 00:32:50.200
I want to try, I want to work things out for myself.

272
00:32:50.200 --> 00:33:02.700
Now, that's just me as a voter, but what I want is I want a political system that I can trust to work stuff out on its own, rather than me telling it what the conclusion that it should come to.

273
00:33:03.440 --> 00:33:05.840
So, that's what we do with juries.

274
00:33:05.840 --> 00:33:08.320
We say, we don't know whether this person is guilty or not.

275
00:33:08.320 --> 00:33:09.280
It's up to you.

276
00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:10.540
You do your best.

277
00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:14.760
You learn a lot, you deliberate a lot, and you decide.

278
00:33:14.760 --> 00:33:24.220
And if you can come to a strong consensus, if a jury of 12 splits 7-5, no one cares very much.

279
00:33:24.220 --> 00:33:30.660
I mean, I wouldn't necessarily say that's a basis on which to find someone guilty or not.

280
00:33:30.660 --> 00:33:44.040
But if they split 10-2, then I think that that's strong evidence to say, we're making a decision on behalf of the community, the community thinks you're guilty or your community thinks you're not guilty.

281
00:33:44.040 --> 00:33:49.180
So that's a way to get at the considered opinion of the people.

282
00:33:49.180 --> 00:33:52.740
So anyway, those are a couple of things.

283
00:33:52.740 --> 00:33:55.700
But I wish them well and maybe they'll do some good.

284
00:33:56.320 --> 00:34:14.440
I think the thing I've noticed is that essentially, the difference sounds like there's a communication between the people in a jury room, while within, say, the MyVote, it's a bit more like everybody makes their own decision after reading.

285
00:34:14.900 --> 00:34:20.380
And one of the things we know is that if you put people in, I call it the road rage effect.

286
00:34:20.380 --> 00:34:38.440
I don't know how many people who are listening to this have had an experience where you're driving somewhere, let's say driving home from work or you're driving back home from somewhere, and somebody does something on the road and it really annoys you, and you might even blow your horn and you go into a bit of a road rage story.

287
00:34:38.440 --> 00:34:40.159
And you might be right, you might be wrong.

288
00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:44.020
They might have done something silly or you might have missed a road sign or something.

289
00:34:44.020 --> 00:34:46.000
Now, I've had this experience once or twice.

290
00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:48.300
I don't think I blew my horn by a nail.

291
00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:55.560
And then I realized that the person next to me is my next door neighbor, and we're both driving to the same place, and we're both going to get out of the car.

292
00:34:55.560 --> 00:34:59.880
And then the road rage me has to present myself to my next door neighbor.

293
00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:09.500
And I'm immediately ashamed about the road rage me, because that's not my neighborly me, and it's not the way I relate to people when I meet them.

294
00:35:09.500 --> 00:35:11.140
And so the whole reason...

295
00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:16.340
It's kind of also because you know that your neighbor intention isn't to cause problems.

296
00:35:16.500 --> 00:35:18.060
Exactly, exactly.

297
00:35:18.060 --> 00:35:23.020
And most people on the road are like that, and they might go, Oh, yeah, I'm sorry about that.

298
00:35:23.020 --> 00:35:28.680
But they get really annoyed with you because you've sat on the horn and been really horrible to them.

299
00:35:28.680 --> 00:35:30.360
And that's the...

300
00:35:30.360 --> 00:35:36.740
And I think of elections and the way we cover media as the politics of road rage.

301
00:35:36.740 --> 00:35:42.980
And if you listen to Alan Jones or we've got sort of slightly more demure versions of that.

302
00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:47.420
And now Alan Jones is a shock job for people who don't know who he is.

303
00:35:47.420 --> 00:35:49.060
Rush Limbaugh, if you like.

304
00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:52.240
If you listen to these people, they crank everyone up.

305
00:35:52.240 --> 00:35:54.160
They're incredibly self-righteous.

306
00:35:54.160 --> 00:36:02.760
Anyone who doesn't agree with them is a fool and a dreadful person and a social justice warrior or a communist or whatever they are.

307
00:36:02.760 --> 00:36:09.100
It almost reminds me of a comment saying that people describe politics like a football or a war.

308
00:36:09.100 --> 00:36:09.720
Sure.

309
00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:21.480
And one of the things, so if you hold a citizen jury, I'll tell you what happens, what goes through people's minds, because I've seen this in the literature and talked to some people who are involved.

310
00:36:21.480 --> 00:36:33.080
Some people get a letter in the post and it says, you've been selected at random, we would like you to represent the people in a citizen jury, and we're going to talk about nuclear waste or something or other.

311
00:36:33.080 --> 00:36:39.720
And they get this thing and they think, oh, gee, that's exciting, that's good, I'm going to be involved in something.

312
00:36:39.720 --> 00:36:41.220
And they agree to do it.

313
00:36:41.220 --> 00:36:44.280
And then as they go along, they think, oh god, this is politics.

314
00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:48.200
There'll be people outside demonstrating, everyone's going to yell at me.

315
00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:52.740
I don't really know, I can't defend myself that well because I don't know the issue very well.

316
00:36:52.740 --> 00:36:57.340
There'll be all these people, self-righteous, yelling.

317
00:36:57.340 --> 00:36:59.000
Political apathy in some ways.

318
00:36:59.000 --> 00:36:59.900
Yeah, exactly.

319
00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:01.160
It's a good, exactly.

320
00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:08.780
And then they go into the room and they sort of they're sort of a bit let down because nobody's like that.

321
00:37:08.780 --> 00:37:13.660
Or maybe one or two people have got sort of funny looking hair or something, but usually nobody's like that.

322
00:37:13.660 --> 00:37:19.440
And then as they get talking to people, including people who they don't agree with, they go, oh, I get it.

323
00:37:19.440 --> 00:37:21.180
These people are just like me.

324
00:37:21.180 --> 00:37:24.820
Yeah, these are all the other people who don't like politics, most of them.

325
00:37:24.820 --> 00:37:27.300
And most people who don't like politics, they've got political views.

326
00:37:27.300 --> 00:37:34.300
They're sort of quite interested in politics or have or interested in political issues, but they've tuned out of this Punch and Judy show.

327
00:37:34.300 --> 00:37:43.360
And they get right into it, and they will go out of their way to say, well, look, I think this is important, but I realize you think that's important.

328
00:37:43.360 --> 00:37:46.660
So surely we can work away through this.

329
00:37:46.660 --> 00:37:52.060
That is not the sort of spirit that is inhabiting the politics as we know it.

330
00:37:52.100 --> 00:37:57.060
So it's like a codependent, empathetic relationship with a fellow citizen in some race.

331
00:37:57.220 --> 00:37:58.100
Absolutely.

332
00:37:58.100 --> 00:38:16.400
And what it does is it makes the, it makes manifest in the physical situation that you're in, the real nature of politics, which is that you can make it about you or you can make it about them.

333
00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:19.520
But most people would prefer to make it about both of those things.

334
00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:29.440
Most people realize that they're just a, you know, they have a view and they want that view to be acknowledged and listened to and taken account of.

335
00:38:29.460 --> 00:38:32.460
And they know they're just an ordinary person.

336
00:38:32.460 --> 00:38:47.440
Machiavelli, who you may have heard of, wrote in the 16th century about the fact that it's only well, it's only the wealthy, it's only the oligarchs, it's only the powerful who want more and more power.

337
00:38:47.960 --> 00:39:01.020
The ordinary people and the spirit of democracy is, look, we want our government to work properly, we want to be left alone, we want to lead our lives, and we don't want to pick fights with people.

338
00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:08.300
Well, that's not the spirit of democracy that inhabits our democratic system.

339
00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:20.100
And it's within grasp because you just have to get ordinary people, this is what Isegaria means, this is one of the things that's comprehended in Isegaria.

340
00:39:20.100 --> 00:39:21.020
The quality of speech.

341
00:39:21.020 --> 00:39:35.300
Ordinary people, equality of speech, just ordinary people don't want trouble, they want to lead a decent life, get on with their business, and acknowledge others' concerns and try and accommodate them.

342
00:39:35.300 --> 00:39:36.000
Okay.

343
00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:37.440
Thank you very much, definitely.

344
00:39:38.140 --> 00:39:46.180
In terms of Flux and MyVote, what we were talking about in the jury or the Citizen Jury concept was the idea of people talking to each other.

345
00:39:46.180 --> 00:39:56.980
But perhaps if you look at New Democracy and how the, if I remember New Democracy is trying to create an app where you can learn more and discuss amongst each other, isn't the key?

346
00:39:56.980 --> 00:39:58.540
No, I'm unaware of that.

347
00:39:58.540 --> 00:40:00.200
New Democracy mostly puts on the citizen.

348
00:40:00.200 --> 00:40:01.100
Or is it New Vote?

349
00:40:01.100 --> 00:40:02.300
I think it's maybe New Vote.

350
00:40:02.300 --> 00:40:03.240
I have to remember it.

351
00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:05.360
I will put in the description.

352
00:40:05.360 --> 00:40:05.720
Okay.

353
00:40:05.720 --> 00:40:18.580
Well, New Democracy is an NGO, an organization in Sydney which tries to organize lots of citizen juries and the sort of thing that I'm talking about.

354
00:40:18.580 --> 00:40:19.320
Yes.

355
00:40:19.320 --> 00:40:21.720
So perhaps it's New Vote, but let me just describe it.

356
00:40:21.720 --> 00:40:30.060
But basically the idea is there's a website where you could discuss with other people about different issues and provide like a little straw poll.

357
00:40:30.220 --> 00:40:34.360
Is it like a little polling mechanism so you know in general what they are?

358
00:40:34.360 --> 00:40:34.640
Yeah.

359
00:40:34.640 --> 00:40:36.180
Are you talking about your view?

360
00:40:36.180 --> 00:40:39.820
I think you're talking about something I talked about in speech.

361
00:40:39.820 --> 00:40:40.740
Yeah, I think so.

362
00:40:40.740 --> 00:40:54.860
Which way you have, you can look at how many, which way people vote and then you can ask who are the, who, which way, if we give more weight to people who have made the best contribution to the debate.

363
00:40:54.860 --> 00:40:55.080
Yeah.

364
00:40:55.080 --> 00:41:16.960
So this was like the thing here is if you could do that online, why not like just integrated with say MyVoteFlux and like just not have to do citizen juries of random selection, just get the opinion of everybody, but have to discuss amongst themselves, do you think say the structure of the programs you're talking about?

365
00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:17.260
Yeah.

366
00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:24.260
Well, we haven't yet mastered the art of stopping trolls driving everybody crazy.

367
00:41:24.260 --> 00:41:31.700
Like you know what I'm referring to, because like some of the objection to citizen juries is that it's a very small sample.

368
00:41:31.700 --> 00:41:40.920
It's not the whole sample and with Flux and MyVote, if it's applied to the whole population, that's the everybody been deciding on it rather than say a random selection.

369
00:41:40.920 --> 00:41:42.680
If that makes sense.

370
00:41:42.680 --> 00:41:43.580
Well, it does make sense.

371
00:41:43.580 --> 00:42:02.940
But if I told you that 60, 65 percent of randomly selected Australians, of a group of 150 randomly selected Australians wanted to do something, I, you know, that's good evidence that that's what the considered opinion people is.

372
00:42:03.340 --> 00:42:06.420
If it was 51 percent, that's not the case.

373
00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:14.100
So, so, so that's how I respond to this idea that the it's a small sample.

374
00:42:15.420 --> 00:42:29.400
Now there is the question of how you try to use new technologies to scale up the capacity of our democracy to take on board diverse perspectives.

375
00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:54.280
We are, we have not made much progress, not that we've really tried to tragically with this has not been something that, you know, I mean, vast amounts of commercial money have gone into Facebook and Twitter, and they're not only not trying to solve this problem, they're probably making the problem worse by just trying to maximize clicks and rev everybody up.

376
00:42:55.360 --> 00:43:09.380
How we build online tools which amp down the aggro and help to qualify who's making the best contribution, I've written a little bit about that.

377
00:43:09.380 --> 00:43:12.300
If people want to go to my, I can send you a link to it.

378
00:43:12.300 --> 00:43:12.800
Thank you.

379
00:43:12.800 --> 00:43:15.820
But it's not something that we've developed very much.

380
00:43:15.820 --> 00:43:26.300
And I think my vote is sort of trying to come up with a system in which there would be responsible discussion.

381
00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:30.180
It's pretty hard, though, to stop irresponsible discussion.

382
00:43:30.180 --> 00:43:50.000
So if anyone wants to read a book by Peter Rushen, who lives in England, Peter Pomerantsev, called This Is Not Propaganda, he documents how Russian trolls, how important Twitter trolls, Facebook trolls, and so on have been to Putin.

383
00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:57.760
He doesn't talk that much about Trump, probably Duarte in the Philippines, who seems like a maniac.

384
00:43:57.760 --> 00:44:01.940
He's done extremely well out of trolling.

385
00:44:01.940 --> 00:44:04.480
Like a not very democratic person, is that what you're saying?

386
00:44:04.480 --> 00:44:05.960
Like an authoritarian kind of person.

387
00:44:05.960 --> 00:44:16.960
Well, he's an authoritarian kind of person who has led a pogrom, a kind of massacre against alleged drug dealers.

388
00:44:16.960 --> 00:44:22.160
Now, some of them will have been drug dealers, and people go out at night, and they assassinate them.

389
00:44:22.160 --> 00:44:23.000
Oh, yeah, yeah.

390
00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:35.420
Now, so there is this undercurrent of around the world of an increase in rise in authoritarianism, more perceptibly over the last like five years or so.

391
00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:54.500
And yeah, well, well, what's now an important part of what's going on there from my reading, which is, you know, I'm not claiming to be an expert, but an important part of what's going on there is that you have, and I recommend if people want to put Peter Pomerantsev into Google and have a look at some of his articles.

392
00:44:54.500 --> 00:45:08.880
Essentially, what happens is that trolls go online and they undermine people's ability to know what's real and what's not real, and who's saying what and why.

393
00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:15.920
So that's something that my vote and all these organizations have to try and deal with.

394
00:45:16.720 --> 00:45:20.900
And I'm not really up on how they're going, but this is...

395
00:45:20.900 --> 00:45:26.260
Facebook, if I remember, and Twitter also, they're trying to tackle this kind of thing as well.

396
00:45:26.260 --> 00:45:28.620
Well, Facebook cannot...

397
00:45:28.620 --> 00:45:32.020
Facebook's comments can't be taken seriously.

398
00:45:32.020 --> 00:45:34.160
They're basically just trying to make money.

399
00:45:34.160 --> 00:45:36.980
Twitter is trying to do things, but it's very hard.

400
00:45:36.980 --> 00:45:38.840
It's very hard.

401
00:45:39.660 --> 00:45:48.260
Any of your listeners can right now go on Twitter and just upset people, just turn up and start abusing them.

402
00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:50.280
And that's how you get more followers.

403
00:45:50.280 --> 00:45:52.740
That's how you join a tribe.

404
00:45:52.740 --> 00:46:00.280
Yeah, like the current issue these days, like in the beginning of the year, has been about bushfire and the coronavirus in Australia.

405
00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:01.000
Yeah.

406
00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:08.500
And if you remember some of the rumors going on with coronavirus, like drinking beer will help cure coronavirus.

407
00:46:08.500 --> 00:46:11.120
It's probably not something you should trust.

408
00:46:11.120 --> 00:46:11.320
Yeah.

409
00:46:11.320 --> 00:46:13.840
Well, that's just disinformation.

410
00:46:13.940 --> 00:46:33.740
But when you have disinformation about who you are talking to, and what their motives are, and whether they're bots, and whether they're funded by the Kremlin, or by Duarte in the Philippines, or by some oligarch somewhere.

411
00:46:33.940 --> 00:46:36.500
And this, you know, like that's what's going on.

412
00:46:37.300 --> 00:46:43.840
And again, I mention those things because they're very much on my mind, and they should be on everybody's minds who's thinking about democracy.

413
00:46:44.600 --> 00:46:54.020
But a Citizen Jury does create a, does a lot of things to make it hard to infiltrate by the trolls.

414
00:46:54.020 --> 00:47:00.340
You know who these people are, they're on the electoral rolls, they're all talking to each other, they get plenty of time.

415
00:47:00.340 --> 00:47:08.540
If people turn up with a conspiracy theory or two, they can tell it to other people, the other people, then the group can say, let's get some research done on that.

416
00:47:08.540 --> 00:47:19.240
And so, with a Citizen Jury, like in practice, if you're saying you're implementing Citizen Juries in the government, would it be like all recorded, the discussion and?

417
00:47:19.440 --> 00:47:33.640
I mean, that's a detail, but there are some people who think that the identities of these people, someone might be able to, you might give someone the option to participate without their identity being known.

418
00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:37.880
But they're not trolls, in the sense that they happen to have been somebody who's randomly selected.

419
00:47:37.980 --> 00:47:41.120
And in that sense, they have an entitlement to be there.

420
00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:44.140
A certain accountability mechanism in that sense.

421
00:47:44.140 --> 00:47:45.160
Well, yes.

422
00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:46.080
Well, there is not.

423
00:47:46.260 --> 00:47:55.640
But remember, one of the beauties of a jury is that the accountability to the people is being of the people, not in reporting back to the people.

424
00:47:55.640 --> 00:47:56.400
I see.

425
00:47:56.400 --> 00:48:00.400
So if, because you're not accountable for your vote, OK?

426
00:48:00.400 --> 00:48:02.040
You just have your vote.

427
00:48:02.040 --> 00:48:05.020
You are sovereign and you vote, and that is accepted.

428
00:48:05.360 --> 00:48:09.200
No one turns up and says justify why you voted, OK?

429
00:48:09.200 --> 00:48:10.460
That's an interesting way of looking at it.

430
00:48:10.460 --> 00:48:12.740
Well, that's a good way of looking at it.

431
00:48:12.740 --> 00:48:16.300
Now, that's why we say our representatives are accountable.

432
00:48:16.300 --> 00:48:21.380
We have a mechanism, it's called an election, which makes them accountable to us.

433
00:48:21.380 --> 00:48:28.140
The mechanism of a jury is not a mechanism of accountability in the same way.

434
00:48:29.420 --> 00:48:38.560
A juror is accountable to themself and their conscience and their sense that, well, they're also accountable to the law.

435
00:48:38.980 --> 00:48:41.640
There are things they are not permitted to do in the jury.

436
00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:46.760
They can't hand out money and try and induce people to come to a different view.

437
00:48:48.700 --> 00:48:51.820
So in that, so they're accountable to the law.

438
00:48:51.820 --> 00:48:58.240
But we don't imagine that somebody can look inside a conscience or that someone can hold them accountable.

439
00:48:58.240 --> 00:49:07.420
We say, if there is an overwhelming consensus of this randomly selected group, we'll take that to be the considered opinion of the people.

440
00:49:07.440 --> 00:49:08.480
I see.

441
00:49:08.480 --> 00:49:19.160
And the problem with existing mechanisms of accountability is, accountability is a nice name, but like transparency, it's got its limitations.

442
00:49:20.300 --> 00:49:29.740
And it always produces its own perversities, because people try and get around accountability, just like they try and get around transparency.

443
00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:31.680
Nice.

444
00:49:31.680 --> 00:49:44.520
So I think we've been talking a bit about citizen juries, and I'd be interested to know, like, what are you aware of so far about citizen juries in Australia, and maybe around the ground, what organization exist?

445
00:49:44.520 --> 00:49:49.160
Well, I think there have been something like 14 citizen juries in Australia.

446
00:49:49.160 --> 00:49:51.760
Virtually all of them have been very successful now.

447
00:49:51.760 --> 00:50:03.560
People who know something will go for and say, the South Australian citizen jury on nuclear waste didn't give the government what it wanted, but it did surface the considered opinion of the people.

448
00:50:03.560 --> 00:50:09.060
It wasn't a brilliantly run citizen jury, and it produced some frustration.

449
00:50:09.300 --> 00:50:18.520
Almost all of the others have been highly successful in that they have arrived at conclusions, and those conclusions have been handed to government.

450
00:50:18.520 --> 00:50:24.400
And when they've been easy to implement, governments have implemented them, and when they've not been easy to implement, guess what happens.

451
00:50:24.400 --> 00:50:31.720
Now, that's why I want to go further than these often government commissioned citizen juries.

452
00:50:31.720 --> 00:50:38.220
If a government is going to commission a citizen jury, you can be pretty sure that it will do so in an area that is pretty tame.

453
00:50:39.740 --> 00:50:44.240
And so they've got a good chance of taking the recommendations and implementing them.

454
00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:54.040
So, for instance, two I know of were in Adelaide, and one was on making Adelaide's nightlife more vibrant but safe.

455
00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:58.160
That's a nice tame issue for politicians, and not one they were doing very well on.

456
00:50:58.160 --> 00:51:00.920
So why is it important that it be a tame kind of issue?

457
00:51:00.920 --> 00:51:09.860
Well, because politicians spend most of their time trying to keep things under control, and their bureaucrats are even more terrified about things not being under control.

458
00:51:09.860 --> 00:51:11.960
So they wouldn't do it on tax.

459
00:51:11.960 --> 00:51:16.120
They wouldn't do it on something which would then just give them a big political headache.

460
00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:18.460
Extremely contagious issues.

461
00:51:18.460 --> 00:51:20.440
Exactly.

462
00:51:20.440 --> 00:51:27.100
And some of the best uses of a citizen jury would be on those kinds of things, precisely for that reason.

463
00:51:29.500 --> 00:51:37.140
So maybe we'll, like, I remember I definitely will be interested in going into more about the efforts that you're personally going through.

464
00:51:37.140 --> 00:51:42.820
But I have recovered through all the things so far before, or is there anything else extra we need to?

465
00:51:42.820 --> 00:51:45.900
Well, you asked about what was happening offshore with citizen juries.

466
00:51:45.900 --> 00:51:46.080
Yes, yes.

467
00:51:46.080 --> 00:51:46.820
And quite a lot.

468
00:51:46.820 --> 00:51:53.780
So in the US state of Oregon, citizen juries have been built into their constitution.

469
00:51:53.780 --> 00:52:07.600
I don't mean they've actually been written into the constitution document, but the way the government works is that there is an entitlement, if you manage to get enough signatures to have a citizen-initiated referendum.

470
00:52:07.600 --> 00:52:12.280
Now, they know, and this has been in the constitution for over 100 years, I think.

471
00:52:12.280 --> 00:52:27.820
Now, people became very unhappy about that because the citizen's initiated referendum was used by well-funded lobbies to put laws in place precisely to serve vested interests.

472
00:52:27.820 --> 00:52:41.080
And as a result, what they've done is they've established a process in which if you have a citizen's initiated referendum, you also have a citizen's review.

473
00:52:41.080 --> 00:52:48.440
And a citizen's review involves a four-day citizen jury with 24 randomly selected jurors.

474
00:52:48.900 --> 00:52:59.100
And often those jurors come to different conclusions to the conclusions that are demonstrated in opinion polls.

475
00:52:59.100 --> 00:53:16.660
And those people then advise the rest of the people so that when you get your paper to vote, it has either on the paper or in the package that you receive 300 words for and against and tells you how many people voted for and how many people voted against.

476
00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:20.240
So that's an example in Oregon, in the United States.

477
00:53:20.720 --> 00:53:34.260
In a province of Belgium now, the Germans speaking, two provinces of Belgium, they have a citizen assembly or a citizen council, a council, I think it's of 50 people chosen at random.

478
00:53:34.260 --> 00:53:44.820
And they perform a role quite like, in some respects, quite like the Athenian Bulle, which is that they're randomly selected and they provide an agenda.

479
00:53:46.380 --> 00:53:56.860
They can say to the legislature, we want you to address these issues, and they can also say, we want you to do this thing.

480
00:53:56.860 --> 00:54:02.040
And they can also commission other citizen juries about specific issues.

481
00:54:02.040 --> 00:54:11.820
Now, also Madrid, the city of Madrid has a randomly selected council, and I'm not entirely sure of it.

482
00:54:11.820 --> 00:54:15.200
It has a different structure, so this is starting to happen.

483
00:54:15.200 --> 00:54:23.540
And of course, there's been large citizen assemblies in France on climate change and in the UK on climate change.

484
00:54:23.540 --> 00:54:24.540
Nice.

485
00:54:24.540 --> 00:54:28.560
Well, that covers pretty much everything from the current situation.

486
00:54:28.560 --> 00:54:28.820
Okay.

487
00:54:28.820 --> 00:54:37.260
So tell me a bit more about how are you going to tackle citizen juries and giving this kind of idea to Australia?

488
00:54:37.260 --> 00:54:37.720
Sure.

489
00:54:37.720 --> 00:54:50.200
So I think everything I've said, it is possible to do the thing that I think is really important is that we don't have to go to the political system and ask for permission to do any of this.

490
00:54:50.200 --> 00:55:45.480
If we can get funding, and that is if people want to crowd fund, but also if I can get some funding from some philanthropic sources, we could set up a standing citizens chamber that could simply be what I want it to be, which is a chamber in which we see the political business of the nation hashed over by ordinary people coming to views, getting to votes, and we would know, for instance, when Tony Abbott is trying to abolish carbon pricing in 2012, sorry, 2014, if he got rid of it then, if it wasn't earlier, 2013, we would know what a citizen council thought of that, and my very strong hunch is they wouldn't have been impressed.

491
00:55:45.480 --> 00:55:49.800
And it wasn't that easy for Tony Abbott to get that through the Senate.

492
00:55:49.800 --> 00:56:02.200
So I think we could have a big impact right now if we could fund a standing citizen chamber and then we could see what the considered opinion of the people was.

493
00:56:02.200 --> 00:56:04.400
And I think it would make it harder.

494
00:56:04.400 --> 00:56:11.420
I mean, the current government has a very small majority in the House of Representatives and needs to talk its way through the Senate.

495
00:56:11.420 --> 00:56:30.140
And I think that doing this would help infuse Australia's party political democracy with Isegaria, with the quality of speech, with the considered opinion of the people, and would have a big influence on the system as it is right now.

496
00:56:30.140 --> 00:56:33.660
We don't have to get anyone's permission to do that.

497
00:56:33.660 --> 00:56:35.240
I see.

498
00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:45.240
So in terms of the citizen jury implementation, like is this, so you're saying this is officially part of the government or is it like a separate?

499
00:56:45.760 --> 00:56:53.160
No, I just said it's privately funded, and it has no official standing, but it would have a lot of political standing.

500
00:56:53.160 --> 00:57:18.120
Because if we can show that these people are ordinary people, and we can show them, and we can show that on this particular matter, for instance, when Scott Morrison said that we should spend less money on bushfire readiness a few months before the bushfires, we would see what the considered opinion of people was.

501
00:57:18.120 --> 00:57:22.620
And we would see what the considered opinion people was on Adani.

502
00:57:22.620 --> 00:57:24.440
Maybe they think it's a good idea.

503
00:57:24.440 --> 00:57:31.500
I think the people, and Adani is a huge coal mine that's proposed for Queensland.

504
00:57:32.140 --> 00:57:37.540
And maybe people in central Queensland would have a different view than other people, and that's good.

505
00:57:37.540 --> 00:57:38.520
We need to know that.

506
00:57:38.520 --> 00:57:40.080
But who knows?

507
00:57:40.080 --> 00:57:59.940
Pardon me for skipping back to a bit before on the beginning of the talk, but what this sort of reminds me of was Penny Rong and many other cases where you have people who are meant to be representative of their people, but at the same time, they have to balance political realities of sticking to party.

508
00:58:00.540 --> 00:58:01.120
That's right.

509
00:58:01.120 --> 00:58:03.620
Well, you're thinking of the same-sex marriage stuff.

510
00:58:03.620 --> 00:58:06.440
Not just that, but there's many other cases as well.

511
00:58:06.440 --> 00:58:17.440
But the idea is that this disjoint between the idea of being a good representative versus the political reality of also being a representative of your ideological party.

512
00:58:17.440 --> 00:58:18.540
Correct.

513
00:58:18.540 --> 00:58:24.160
Well, often it's not an ideological party, it's a party that has debts to vested interests.

514
00:58:24.760 --> 00:58:27.000
So, you know, to survive.

515
00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:27.580
Exactly.

516
00:58:28.320 --> 00:58:31.620
So, I mean, I should make some unpleasant comments about the Labour Party, I suppose.

517
00:58:31.620 --> 00:58:34.800
But for balance, I'm not a huge fan of the Labour Party.

518
00:58:35.880 --> 00:58:45.120
But to take the Liberal Party, I mean, the Liberal Party's and the National Party's views on coal are not particularly rational.

519
00:58:45.800 --> 00:58:47.740
They have two sources, I think.

520
00:58:47.760 --> 00:58:52.540
One is they're funded by the coal lobby, and so that's worth a lot of money to them.

521
00:58:53.000 --> 00:59:09.600
And the second thing is that they've turned it into a kind of culture war thing, where they can play off the views of communities where coal mining takes place against the views of others.

522
00:59:09.600 --> 00:59:31.740
And what doesn't happen, and this is sort of true on both sides, what doesn't happen is no one gets down to try to take the issues as serious as they can, including the issues, the local issues of adjustment, and then say, all right, what do we, how do we all get to a situation where we're a bit happier about what's going on in the situation we have at the moment.

523
00:59:31.740 --> 00:59:33.340
I see.

524
00:59:33.340 --> 00:59:36.700
So back to the implementation of the citizen juries.

525
00:59:36.700 --> 00:59:51.360
So given that this is a privately run citizen jury organization as the concept, some things I think you may also need to try to get is some ways of being able to find the electoral role to be able to run the select.

526
00:59:51.360 --> 00:59:55.000
Well, I think the electoral role is public document.

527
00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:55.800
Public document.

528
00:59:55.800 --> 00:59:56.480
Okay.

529
00:59:56.480 --> 00:59:57.100
I see.

530
00:59:57.100 --> 01:00:06.560
So in that sense, is there much barrier to like in terms of implementation of implementing this organization or technical barriers?

531
01:00:06.560 --> 01:00:06.920
No, no.

532
01:00:06.920 --> 01:00:12.780
I mean, there are privately, people have the ability to run these things privately.

533
01:00:12.780 --> 01:00:14.820
If you need some funding, it's not the right chief to do it.

534
01:00:14.820 --> 01:00:23.220
So it's kind of like Roy Morgan in some ways, like a statistical organization, but with a lot more deliberation, but that's exactly right.

535
01:00:23.220 --> 01:00:26.040
It's a form of polling, but it's deliberative polling.

536
01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:26.820
Deliberative polling.

537
01:00:26.820 --> 01:00:27.060
Yeah.

538
01:00:27.060 --> 01:00:28.040
That's another way to do it.

539
01:00:28.040 --> 01:00:31.640
I remember like when Fishkin is the guy who's written a lot about this.

540
01:00:31.640 --> 01:00:35.560
Like a lot of things, I remember why a guy used to have to do surveys.

541
01:00:36.120 --> 01:00:48.220
And often I sit down and talk to the person, but often the key thing that I was told in the training of doing door-to-door surveys is are meant to be as transparent as possible.

542
01:00:48.220 --> 01:00:49.620
Do not influence the...

543
01:00:49.620 --> 01:00:50.320
Correct.

544
01:00:50.780 --> 01:00:54.320
But the point is that an opinion poll is just that.

545
01:00:54.320 --> 01:00:58.880
It's an opinion poll, and it doesn't tell you anything.

546
01:00:58.880 --> 01:01:02.600
It tells you, often people will say, well, I don't know, and you sort of press them.

547
01:01:02.600 --> 01:01:04.800
Well, if you have to vote tomorrow, who would you vote for?

548
01:01:05.540 --> 01:01:13.400
And the fact is that what you say, you record the opinion of the people, but you have no idea how well-informed it is.

549
01:01:13.400 --> 01:01:38.440
You have no idea how it would hold up under scrutiny or under, you know, or even if you're just interested in this person's state of mind, you don't know whether in a room of 10 people, half of whom disagreed with them and came up with good arguments, whether they change or whether they just feel very strongly that this is a, you know, so if you ask a person about abortion, it's hard to argue one way or the other on abortion.

550
01:01:38.440 --> 01:01:44.540
You happen to have views and they depend on the way you look at human life and maybe religious commitments and so on.

551
01:01:44.540 --> 01:01:49.860
Whereas with other things, you, as people learn more, they can change their minds.

552
01:01:49.860 --> 01:01:52.040
And polling doesn't tell you anything about that.

553
01:01:53.020 --> 01:01:57.300
But this kind of searching for the considered opinion of the people does.

554
01:01:57.300 --> 01:02:09.720
Isn't that kind of the reason is because the purpose of an opinion survey is often tied to business interests of you're trying to sell a product to the population.

555
01:02:09.720 --> 01:02:10.240
Exactly.

556
01:02:10.240 --> 01:02:14.520
And you're trying to, if there are prejudices there, you go with that.

557
01:02:14.520 --> 01:02:18.080
If people think, I don't mean racial prejudice or anything like that.

558
01:02:18.260 --> 01:02:22.680
I was talking about selling furbies, like selling more furbies.

559
01:02:22.680 --> 01:02:23.140
Exactly.

560
01:02:23.180 --> 01:02:27.140
So people have a kind of, and this is the same with focus groups.

561
01:02:27.140 --> 01:02:28.740
They're not deliberative processes.

562
01:02:28.740 --> 01:02:29.860
You're not trying to push people.

563
01:02:29.860 --> 01:02:33.860
You say things like, what's your impression of Australia?

564
01:02:33.860 --> 01:02:38.660
And they'll say, well, rugged individualism and popping a prawn on the barbie or something.

565
01:02:38.660 --> 01:02:41.920
And you'll go away and make an ad out of that.

566
01:02:41.920 --> 01:02:44.440
And you'll just go with whatever's on the surface.

567
01:02:44.820 --> 01:02:50.620
I think I like that, because you remember a few years ago you did a talk with us.

568
01:02:50.620 --> 01:02:57.400
