717
01:15:37.660 --> 01:15:55.220
And I'll just tie in with the last thought that I remembered is I remembered a while ago in terms of the Brexit system about this concept of maybe a that a nation probably would want to have a department for like a state philosopher.

718
01:15:55.220 --> 01:16:05.080
And the idea behind the problem of the Brexit issue is that it was the problem wasn't the choices made of yes and no, but the question behind it.

719
01:16:05.380 --> 01:16:05.680
Absolutely.

720
01:16:05.680 --> 01:16:11.980
And so would a state philosopher be an interesting approach to tackling this?

721
01:16:11.980 --> 01:16:14.880
Completely stupid idea as far as I'm concerned.

722
01:16:14.880 --> 01:16:29.880
But certainly it's true that the question was a stupid question, because what it did is it pitted a completely non-specific option not to be in the EU with a very specific option, which is we are now in the EU and everybody knows what it looks like.

723
01:16:29.880 --> 01:16:43.960
And what happened in Brexit contrasts very unfavorably with what John Howard insisted on regarding the Republic, which is he said, I don't want to go to an election in which is, do we want a Republic or a monarchy?

724
01:16:43.960 --> 01:16:51.660
I want to go to an election in which we have a concrete model of a monarchy and the Republicans can work out what their model of a Republic is.

725
01:16:51.660 --> 01:17:04.480
Now, there are arguments the other way, but your philosopher or maybe it needs to be a mathematician, can explain that there is no perfect way through that three-cornered contest.

726
01:17:04.480 --> 01:17:08.520
If you run it in one particular way, you can come up with one answer.

727
01:17:08.520 --> 01:17:12.740
If you run it in another way, you will get another answer and both answers.

728
01:17:12.740 --> 01:17:16.400
You can tell a story in which each of these pathways is legitimate.

729
01:17:16.400 --> 01:17:17.520
It's like gerrymandering.

730
01:17:18.660 --> 01:17:19.240
Well, exactly.

731
01:17:19.240 --> 01:17:31.920
I mean, John Howard was trying to gerrymander the system in his own favor, but at least it put Australians in a position where they got asked, what I call the Spice Girls question, which is tell me what you want, what you really, really want.

732
01:17:31.920 --> 01:17:42.140
Because the Republicans were so split, the monarchists made hay and won the vote.

733
01:17:42.140 --> 01:17:54.880
So it is a reasonable, it's not the only position, but it is a reasonable position for someone to say, if you want to change things, you be specific about what the change is, and then we'll have a voter palette.

734
01:17:54.880 --> 01:17:58.420
And that's what we did in Australia, and the result was we didn't change.

735
01:17:58.420 --> 01:18:01.920
It's not what they did in the United Kingdom.

736
01:18:01.920 --> 01:18:09.980
And they got a change, and it's a catastrophic change, not a catastrophic change, a minor disaster of a change.

737
01:18:09.980 --> 01:18:10.740
Thank you very much.

738
01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:11.780
Thanks, Brian.

739
01:18:11.780 --> 01:18:18.640
